snippet.textDisplay:
As a Stockholmer, I can't help but compare Crossrail with Stockholm's Citybanan. Two commuter rail tunnels, extremely similar in function, but on completely different scales.

The stations especially have a very similar feel, and my first thought setting foot in Citybanan on the opening day was the same as yours in this video. It really was unlike anything I'd seen before. It feels more like walking around an airport than a subway station. Great video, and would love to see more videos like this, visiting the site and with interviews!

snippet.textDisplay:
One aspect I suspect is a failure in design of these is the distances you need to traverse to use it. All these constructions are huge when they perhaps didn't have to be.
What if you made the trains and tunnels smaller and serialized the traffic and brought the tunnel up to shallower depth to very minimal station. Maybe far more stations and far more tunnels.
What if a train had only a couple of seats and ran constantly. What if a station was on a side track and carts not headed for that station would skip by below ground. What if they were autonomous taxi pods running on underground road system. What if they could even come up and drive on roads where necessary.

snippet.textDisplay: JESUS CHRIST THAT’S AN INCREDIBLE INTERIOR.😮 iIm glad they haven’t gone overboard with the interior in terms of padding everything in glass, even though it’s still a very modern interior. I really don’t like the main open spaces though separate from the main platforms, but the actual tunnels themselves seem very in keeping with London’s curved tiles aesthetic, even though they actually aren’t made of ceramiciles this time. I think I would’ve preferred it if the rest of the new cross rail had more Victorian themes to it. I.e., more red brick and perhaps some iron vaulting, metalwork and statuettes at different intervals along the columns to really help it blend together with what really makes it London, rather than just any other place in the rest of the world. We cannot forget who we are.
